    "solution": "<p><img alt=\"JEE Main 2026 (Online) 4th April Morning Shift Chemistry - Chemical Bonding &amp; Molecular Structure Question 1 English Explanation\" src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/6y3zli1moqy0pbl/9f27bfcd-abfa-49ee-93aa-5e9022abad85/03875a10-4794-11f1-b09b-174532b396c4/file-6y3zli1moqy0pbm.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/6y3zli1moqy0pbl/9f27bfcd-abfa-49ee-93aa-5e9022abad85/03875a10-4794-11f1-b09b-174532b396c4/file-6y3zli1moqy0pbm.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\"></p>\n<p>In the ion $\\mathrm{XeO}_6{ }^{4-}$, xenon (Xe) is the central atom and it is bonded to $6$ oxygen atoms.</p>\n<p>Each Xe–O bond has one bond pair of electrons, and in Lewis theory each single bond is counted as one $\\sigma$ bond.</p>\n<p>So, the number of $\\sigma$ bond-pairs around Xe is $6$.</p>\n<p>In this structure, xenon uses all its available electron pairs for bonding with the $6$ oxygen atoms, so there is no electron pair left as a lone pair on Xe.</p>\n<p>$$\\therefore $$ $\\begin{aligned} &amp; \\sigma=6  &amp; \\text { Lone pairs }=0\\end{aligned}$</p>",
    "__v": 0,
    "title": "JEE Main 2026 (Online) 4th April Morning Shift"
  },
